title: Great Parks of Africa
subTitle: The Addo Elephant Park was founded in 1931 and is 1,640km2. It hosts more than 450 elephants and other mammals and was created in response to the elephant population falling as low as eleven.

title: Great Parks of Africa
subTitle: Table Mountain National Park on the southwestern tip of Africa surrounded by ocean and humanity. It is a rugged peninsula jutting out into the cold Atlantic Ocean and forming an island of incredible diversity.

title: Great Parks of Africa
subTitle: In the northeastern corner of South Africa lays a land of unparalleled beauty that encompasses pristine beaches and vibrant coral reefs, lush wetlands and lakes, and vast forests and open plains. Each landscape provides sanctuary for a range of animals. Known locally as the Miracle, due to its beauty, this is the magical world of iSimangaliso.

title: Great Parks of Africa
subTitle: In the centre of South Africa is an ancient landscape that was once an inland sea. Now it is a mosaic of unique habitats. Life here has evolved ingenious solutions to survive. There is nowhere in South Africa quite like the Karoo National Park.

title: Great Parks of Africa
subTitle: In the southern reaches of Africa's great Kalahari basin, everything is made tough. Ancient rivers harbour water deep underground, and these hidden lifelines forge a fragile link to survival. This is the Kgalagadi Transfrontier Park.

title: Wild Africa: Rivers of Life
subTitle: On the Luangwa River, the law of the land is dictated by the ever-changing seasons and the constant cycle of life. In the wet season the Luangwa Valley is a green paradise, as the waters flow in abundance and lush green vegetation carpets the landscape. But in the dry season, when rains become but a distant memory, the greenery turns brown and the water levels drop by a foot per day.

title: Wild Africa: Rivers of Life
subTitle: For four months of the year, the powerful Limpopo river revitalises the landscape, nourishing the abundance of wildlife dependent on it. For the remaining seven months its waters are locked away in inaccessible underground aquifers, leaving behind a series of small and ever-shrinking muddy pools. Excruciating heat and drought ravage the area until the next rains.

title: Wild Africa: Rivers of Life
subTitle: The Hoanib River runs for 170 miles, rising in the Hoanib Valley in Namibia, and flowing through the parched Namib Desert all the way to the Skeleton Coast before emptying into the Atlantic Ocean. The river only flows for two weeks a year, but it shapes and invigorates the landscape and all that it touches.

title: Wild Africa: Rivers of Life
subTitle: Once a year, a flood engulfs the the Okavango Delta, a wetland surrounded by arid plains, and creates a haven for wildlife.
